        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down. | Bromley. | Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Nov 2.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Many thanks about the index. I have returned the M.S. with a note to M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Dallas; it seems very well done but rather too full.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>With respect to the story of a hybrid from an ass and a bull (for I presume you refer to such) it is utterly incredible.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> Many similar stories have been propagated, but on investigation have proved entirely false.</p>
<p>The explanation has generally been a slight monstrosity.</p>
<p>My dear Sir | yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5670.xml" resp="#automat">letter from W. S. Dallas, 4 November 1867</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1179.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Sweetland Dallas’s</ref> specimen of the index for <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5661.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Murray, 1 November [1867]</ref>). Neither the enclosure nor CD’s note to Dallas has been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5661.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Murray, 1 November [1867]</ref> and n. 4.</note>
        </div>        
            
